publisher="Apress",
address="Berkeley, CA",
pages="133--156",
abstract="What of the home in the future then? How will designers, architects, technologists, anthropologists, and politicians imagine us to live? Far from being able to gaze that far ahead in the future, it's clear from the past hundred years that some things may stay the same but be experienced differently. The idea of the home as a private space has been complicated by a variety of ``always on'' appliances, selling us services instead of products. Middle class and wealthy households in the West might miss the days of in-house servants and emulate their presence by using voice assistants and on-demand services supported by the so-called ``gig economy.'' Culturesare also looking to new technologies to create a collectively agreeable view of what ``good'' home living entails. We are always trying to get a peek through the curtains and understand how we compare to others when it comes to the ways we live, and new technologies will continue to support home owners in that quest to ``keep up with the Jones'.'' We are always on the fence with what we consider to be private.",
