pages="245--253",
abstract="Rapid technological advances and new models of aging highlight the potential of smart homes to support older adults and promote independence. A ``smart home'' is a residential setting with embedded technological features that enable passive monitoring of the well-being and activities of their residents aiming to improve primarily overall quality of life, to detect or even prevent emergencies and ultimately increase independence for the involved residents. Efforts to design, implement and evaluate such systems have been underway for several years now, targeting specifically older adults or people with disabilities or the general population. This chapter reviews existing smart home initiatives for healthy aging that utilize diverse sets of technologies (e.g., cameras, motion sensors, radio frequency identifiers) and serve various goals (e.g., monitor mobility, detect emergencies). We discuss ethical and practical considerations and outline the gaps in current scientific evidence and future trends.",
