abstract="Analogies abound in the business literature as the competition among business consultants to find the latest silver bullet in organizational thinking increases. Josephine Green, ex-senior director of trends and strategy at Philips Design, draws the picture of pyramids and pancakes to demonstrate the impact of new technology on organizational model development (Green, 2007). Ori Brafman and Rod Beckstrom conjure up the twin metaphors of the starfish and the spider to contrast the supposedly revolutionary peer-to-peer `leaderless' model and the traditional top-down model (Brafman and Beckstrom, 2006). Other organizational specialists borrow from the theories of evolutionary biology, such as Richard Dawkins's selfish gene theory, to argue that ideas, like memes, have a life of their own in this networked organism, and morph, according to the principles of natural selection, across multiple nodes, as in some self-replicating environmental science experiment (Dawkins, 1990). Thus a new orthodoxy in organizational thinking has emerged whereby organizational experts claim to explain human behaviour within online social networks as if the phenomena observed had appeared by the power of some kind of magic. Even the acclaimed Charles Leadbeater We-Think model, which is arguably less gimmicky and more substantial than the analogies cited above, and which is widely used in educational and corporate circles, falls into the same trap of striving to encapsulate the complexity of new organizational principles in one simplistic, compelling, and mostly misleading, concept (Leadbeater, 2008).",
