year="2012",
publisher="Springer New York",
address="New York, NY",
pages="185--208",
abstract="For caregivers of persons with disabilities, the importance of their caregiving can be reflected on a continuum that at one end supports the beginning of life and at the other end supports the end of life (see Fig. 12.1). Since the early 1980s, infants who needed a medical device to compensate for a vital organ or body function and were thus technology dependent, have been sent home from the hospital with their parent caregivers because of cost reductions and better developmental outcomes for the children (Cross et al., Issues in Comprehensive Pediatric Nursing 21:63--84, 1998). One of the most critical factors that determined whether technology-dependent children had extended hospital stays or were able to be cared for at home was the ability and commitment of the parent caregivers to manage the technology (Cross et al., Issues in Comprehensive Pediatric Nursing 21:63--84, 1998; Odom and Chandler, Early Childhood Special Education 9(4): 43--54, 1990; Perkins, Journal of Pediatric Nursing 8(1): 2--9, 1993). Likewise, when support is needed at the end of life, caregivers of a family member in the final stages of life secondary to a disorder or condition such as amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, Huntington's disease, or cancer often must master technologies to administer oxygen, nourishment, and pain-relieving medications (Aranda and Hayman-White, Cancer Nursing, 24:300--307, 2001; Caring for people with Huntington's disease, http://endoflifecare.tripod.com/juvenilehuntingtonsdisease/id179.html, 2005; Gibson and Schroder, American Journal of Hospice {\&} Palliative Care 18(1):19--25, 2001; Twilight brigade: Compassion in action, http://www.thetwilightbrigade.com/, 2008). In between the two ends of the caregiving continuum, caregivers use technology to support persons with disabilities so that they can carry out the activities that constitute the fabric of their everyday lives---eating, toileting, bathing, dressing, transferring and communicating, as well as participate in the social roles valued by these persons---such as parent, volunteer, teacher, lawyer, spouse, or coach. Technologies designed to support persons with disabilities also have the potential to reduce the need for personal assistance and reduce caregiver burden.",
isbn="978-1-4614-3384-2",
doi="10.1007/978-1-4614-3384-2_12",
url="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-1-4614-3384-2_12",
