abstract="Wheeled mobile anthropomorphic robots (WMAR's) are very popular due to their increased mobility and stability, and the relatively affordable cost. A WMAR has a mobile platform which very often accommodates inside it the required computer and other hardware equipment. The upper part or torso of WMAR's may have any form from very simple to very complex depending on the application(s) for which they are designed. This chapter discusses the general structure of WMAR's, and provides a conceptual description of two sophisticated WMAR's, namely ARMAR III (Karlsruhe University), and Rollin Justin (DLR: German Aerospace Center). Then, the chapter describes seven available WMAR's designed for social interaction with humans. These robots are: Maggie, Robovie, CosmoBot, Bandit, PEARL, Nexi, and Mobiserv.",
