abstract="This paper describes two studies focusing on acceptance of medical technologies from different points of view -- in general and in particular. Acceptance of medical assistive technologies was analyzed considering influences of user diversity factors. The first study explored how people perceive the aging process itself and showed how this perception is associated with general aspects of acceptance of medical technology in terms of usability. The second study was conducted to analyze acceptance of a specific technology -- a smart robot -- revealing that the acceptance of a concrete medical device is more specific and that especially age and gender form its underlying structures.",
