pages="211--245",
abstract="One of the book's key resources is that the Britannia, latterly known as the Panopticon, or `Pots and Pans', survived into living memory and remains part of the Glasgow's urban folklore for older generations. Reinforcing the thesis of the vibrancy of city centre entertainment culture, this chapter draws on a series of original oral history interviews---with subjects recorded in their seventies and eighties who remember visiting the Panopticon as children in the 1920s and 1930s to see films and live acts---which serve to locate the Panopticon within the broader context of Glasgow's amusement culture and street life of the 1930s. Analysis of the multiple roles of memory in recorded interviews draws on Annette Kuhn's An Everyday Magic: Cinema and Cultural Memory.",
