abstract="Changing clothes is a basic activity of daily living (ADL) which may be used as a measurement of the functional status of e.g. an elderly person, or a person with certain disabilities. In this paper we propose a methodology for the detection of when a human has changed clothes. Our non-contact unobtrusive monitoring system is built upon the Microsoft Kinect depth camera. It uses the OpenNI SDK to detect a human skeleton and extract the upper and lower clothes' visual features. Color, texture and edge descriptors are then extracted and fused. We evaluate our system on a publicly available set of real recordings for several users and under various illumination conditions. Our results show that our system is able to successfully detect when a user changes clothes, thus to assess the quality of the corresponding ADL.",
